","1200":"1200","Abt 1187":"about 1187","1220":"1220","1187":"1187","Abt 1203":"about 1203","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","Abt 1208":"about 1208","1208":"1208",",, England":"England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Simon  , now rare, but more common in the Middle Ages, when it gave rise to the surnames <i>Simms</i> and <i>Simpson</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Simon","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert de Wynynton was born about 1187, in England, United Kingdom as the son of Lidulf de Croxton SheriffofChester. He married Matilda de Wilburgham about 1203, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1294, at the age of 108."},"et":{"Abt 1187–1294":"umbes 1187–1294","1187–1294":"1187–1294","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1258–Female":"1258–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","Abt 1187":"umbes 1187","1220":"1220","1187":"1187","Abt 1203":"umbes 1203","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","Abt 1208":"umbes 1208","1208":"1208",",, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1187–1294":"noin 1187–1294","1187–1294":"1187–1294","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1258–Female":"1258–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1208–Female":"1208–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","Abt 1187":"noin 1187","1220":"1220","1187":"1187","Abt 1203":"noin 1203","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","Abt 1208":"noin 1208","1208":"1208",",, England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1187–1294":"environ 1187–1294","1187–1294":"1187–1294","1220–Male